<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="588" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,258,1401]" pageId="7" pageNumber="588">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,1197,1222]" pageId="7" pageNumber="588">Remarks</emphasis>
. The new species is somewhat similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Yang, 1998" authorityName="Yang" authorityYear="1998" box="[779,1076,1198,1222]" class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" genus="Rhaphium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="588" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gansuanum">
<emphasis box="[779,940,1198,1221]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="588">R. gansuanum</emphasis>
Yang, 1998
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingRegion box="[1146,1323,1197,1222]" country="China" name="Gansu" pageId="7" pageNumber="588">Gansu province</collectingRegion>
of 
<collectingCountry box="[1362,1432,1197,1222]" name="China" pageId="7" pageNumber="588">China</collectingCountry>
, but may be separated from the latter by the length / width ratio of the first flagellomere, the color of the legs and the shape of the cercus. In 
<emphasis box="[407,574,1270,1293]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="588">
<taxonomicName box="[407,570,1270,1293]" class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" genus="Rhaphium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="588" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gansuanum">R. gansuanum</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
the first flagellomere is 1.6 times longer than wide; the legs are mainly black but with yellow tibiae; the cercus is thin and long with the inflated base (
<bibRefCitation author="Yang" box="[966,1155,1305,1330]" pageId="7" pageNumber="588" refString="Yang, D., Zhang, L., Wang, M. &amp; Zhu, Y. (2011) Diptera Dolichopodidae. In: Fauna Sinica Insecta. Vol. 53. Science Press, Beijing, pp. 1241 - 1273." type="book" year="2011">
Yang 
<emphasis box="[1032,1081,1305,1329]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="588">et al</emphasis>
. 2011
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="588" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,258,1401]" pageId="7" pageNumber="588">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,326,1341,1366]" pageId="7" pageNumber="588">Etymology</emphasis>
. The word ‘ 
<emphasis box="[468,577,1341,1365]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="588">bisectum’</emphasis>
means being bifurcated twice. The new species is named after the shape of cercus.
</paragraph>
